187
00:15:10,000 --> 00:15:15,040
of research methods, but what I've found over 
doing this for many years is that the biggest  

188
00:15:15,040 --> 00:15:20,480
bang for your buck is doing these kind of deep 
qualitative interviews where I can dig in and  

189
00:15:20,480 --> 00:15:24,960
understand people's stories, understand their 
motivations, understand past experiences, "Why  

190
00:15:24,960 --> 00:15:28,960
did you do this in the past? What have you done 
in the past? What's worked? What hasn't worked?"  

191
00:15:29,480 --> 00:15:34,640
Having the whole team watch that and understand 
and build that kind of empathy and understanding  

192
00:15:34,640 --> 00:15:40,120
and hear those stories is very powerful.
But then we do those in small batches. So  

193
00:15:40,120 --> 00:15:45,000
rather than do an interview on Monday and then one 
on Wednesday and then a couple on Friday, we clump  

194
00:15:45,000 --> 00:15:49,840
them. Ideally, it's in that one day, so I bang 
out five one-hour interviews in one day while the  

195
00:15:49,840 --> 00:15:54,320
whole team's watching. Sometimes we do it across 
two days, depending on time zones and things  

196
00:15:54,320 --> 00:16:01,240
like that, but the idea is that they're clumped 
together. The reason for that is if you do them  

197
00:16:01,240 --> 00:16:08,080
in a clump like that, then the patterns are just 
much more obvious. At the end of the day, it's  

198
00:16:08,080 --> 00:16:11,440
just really clear what were the big takeaways.
It's not going to answer every question that you  

199
00:16:11,440 --> 00:16:16,240
ever had about your product or your customers. 
But the big things that you set out to answer,  

200
00:16:16,240 --> 00:16:20,520
it's pretty clear, like did it work? Did 
it not work? Which parts were good or bad?  

201
00:16:20,520 --> 00:16:24,720
All these kinds of things. And the whole team 
has watched it, and so they have that sense. 

202
00:16:24,720 --> 00:16:31,080
And that idea of just doing five of them, you hit 
what's called data saturation. This is the thing  

203
00:16:31,080 --> 00:16:38,880
in qualitative research where the common version 
of this is everybody, after four or five, is like,  

204
00:16:38,880 --> 00:16:42,280
"Oh, for God's sakes, please don't let me sit 
through any more of these. I get it. I'm hearing  

205
00:16:42,280 --> 00:16:47,760
the same things over and over. I understand. 
Let's move on and do something different,  

206
00:16:47,760 --> 00:16:52,560
change the customer, change the prototypes, 
whatever." So qualitative interviews in  

207
00:16:52,560 --> 00:16:59,480
small clumps, and then we compare prototypes.
And so this kind of comes from that time I had  

208
00:16:59,480 --> 00:17:05,640
at Walmart where I sort of see the whole world as 
a shopping process. And so there's something very  

209
00:17:05,640 --> 00:17:09,800
valuable, just the way any of you have shopped 
for anything, right? You don't look at just one  

210
00:17:09,800 --> 00:17:14,480
thing. If I showed you just one thing, you'd have 
some feedback and you'd have an opinion about it,  

211
00:17:14,480 --> 00:17:18,320
like, "Let's shop for a couch. I like the 
color. The cushions are uncomfortable.  

212
00:17:18,320 --> 00:17:23,280
I like the fabric," or not. And that's 
helpful and that's interesting to hear,  

213
00:17:23,280 --> 00:17:30,960
but as you start looking at two or three, then 
you start having this different reference points. 

214
00:17:30,960 --> 00:17:35,920
And when you're testing with customers, it's 
not up to them to come up with these different  

215
00:17:35,920 --> 00:17:39,360
possibilities of what could be, and so 
if I'm presenting those, they're like,  

216
00:17:39,360 --> 00:17:44,360
"Oh, that's interesting. I like the way this 
one has cushions that are made out of down,  

217
00:17:44,360 --> 00:17:49,360
but this other one is really interesting because 
they deliver it. Oh, but I like this because it's  

218
00:17:49,360 --> 00:17:54,800
a style that I like and they actually take away 
my old couch." So then I can compare and contrast  

219
00:17:54,800 --> 00:18:00,360
across these different possibilities, these 
different distinct value propositions. And I'm  

220
00:18:00,360 --> 00:18:04,720
not looking for a winner but this comparison.
The other big benefit of having multiple  

221
00:18:04,720 --> 00:18:13,240
prototypes is it helps teams avoid getting 
too wed to one specific idea. So you can get a  

222
00:18:13,240 --> 00:18:17,720
little over-committed. There's a risk that you get 
over-committed to one idea, you're polishing that,  

223
00:18:17,720 --> 00:18:23,880
you're working on it, you're too committed to 
that. And this pushes teams to think of new,  

224
00:18:23,880 --> 00:18:28,960
different possibilities, and you can be a little 
bit more neutral and a little bit more objective  

225
00:18:28,960 --> 00:18:36,320
if you're not all so bought into one thing. 
So comparing prototypes becomes very powerful. 

226
00:18:36,320 --> 00:18:42,360
And then the other thing is making this a team 
sport. The watch parties are a key example of  

227
00:18:42,360 --> 00:18:50,240
this. And I'm livestreaming it, so the whole team 
is all watching it these days. Typically, people  

228
00:18:50,240 --> 00:18:55,440
are pretty distributed, so I'm doing it over Zoom 
and they're watching the livestream independently.  

229
00:18:55,440 --> 00:19:01,920
And then one of my partners, so Kate Aronowitz or 
Vanessa Cho, got amazing design partners I get to  

230
00:19:01,920 --> 00:19:07,000
work with, are often facilitating that back room.
And so what they're doing is they're helping the  

231
00:19:07,000 --> 00:19:11,840
team... We have a structured process for taking 
notes, and then in between each interview,  

232
00:19:11,840 --> 00:19:16,080
they're debriefing. So I have this spreadsheet 
that I use that's like, "These are the key things  

233
00:19:16,080 --> 00:19:19,880
we wanted to get out of this." And so they're 
going through and just capturing that, like,  

234
00:19:19,880 --> 00:19:24,280
"What just happened in this interview? Let's make 
sure we have the high level." And at the end of  

235
00:19:24,280 --> 00:19:29,040
the day, we have a way to all capture, like, 
"What were our big takeaways? What happened?" 

236
00:19:29,040 --> 00:19:34,600
But the magic of all watching it and processing 
it and discussing it and debating it through the  

237
00:19:34,600 --> 00:19:40,360
course of the day is that everybody is aligned. 
We've all seen it. I don't write a report. I  

238
00:19:40,360 --> 00:19:45,720
haven't written a report in, I don't know, 
10 years, because at the end, when we capture  

239
00:19:45,720 --> 00:19:50,680
those big takeaways, the team has captured it. 
We do it through Google Form, it shows up in  

240
00:19:50,680 --> 00:19:55,040
the spreadsheet, and we kind of discuss it.
And then everybody's just raring to go do the  

241
00:19:55,040 --> 00:20:00,200
next thing. Everybody's aligned, and there's this 
incredible amount of momentum from the team after  

242
00:20:00,200 --> 00:20:04,680
that. They're like, "Let's go do the next thing." 
It's clear what we need to do and what we learned.  

243
00:20:04,680 --> 00:20:10,720
And sometimes the next thing is do this again and 
adjust so we can build more confidence. But the  

244
00:20:10,720 --> 00:20:17,040
make it a team sport has been this very powerful 
tool for building consensus, building alignment.  

245
00:20:17,040 --> 00:20:20,240
Especially as teams are growing and people are 
going to start up running in different directions,  

246
00:20:20,240 --> 00:20:25,440
it's like a chance to come together and make 
sure, like, "Oh, where are we? What are we doing?"

247
00:20:25,440 --> 00:20:29,360
Awesome. That was really helpful. So just to 
summarize the key elements of this approach,  

248
00:20:29,360 --> 00:20:35,800
there's a bullseye customer concept of just a 
very narrow people wedge, almost, of who would  

249
00:20:35,800 --> 00:20:39,360
most want this thing, and we'll talk more 
about that, making it qualitative versus  

250
00:20:39,360 --> 00:20:46,480
surveys or things like that, comparing 
prototypes, and making it a team sport. 

251
00:20:46,480 --> 00:20:50,040
Okay. So we're going to actually go into more 
detail of each of these steps just so folks  

252
00:20:50,040 --> 00:20:54,120
can... Basically, what I'm hoping to do is 
they... Folks listening to this can do this  

253
00:20:54,120 --> 00:20:58,400
tomorrow or next week. There's a little 
prep time. Before we get into each step,  

254
00:20:58,400 --> 00:21:01,200
when do you recommend people do this? 
When in the stage of a journey? Can  

255
00:21:01,200 --> 00:21:05,120
you do it many times? Any just 
context there before we dive in?

256
00:21:05,120 --> 00:21:11,640
You can do it many times. The key times to do it 
is... At a high level, it's before, hopefully,  

257
00:21:11,640 --> 00:21:19,160
you've invested a lot of time into building 
something, a lot of energy and the team's  

258
00:21:19,160 --> 00:21:24,200
energy and money that goes into the building. 
So it's usually before you build something,  

259
00:21:24,200 --> 00:21:28,240
maybe if you're expanding into a new group of 
customers, so you were killing it in the UK and  

260
00:21:28,240 --> 00:21:32,360
now you're trying to get into the US market and 
that's different, or you worry it's different or  

261
00:21:32,360 --> 00:21:37,400
you're not sure, it's a good time to check.
Or maybe you were selling to enterprise,  

262
00:21:37,400 --> 00:21:40,920
you're doing very white-glove, 
high-touch sales to enterprise,  

263
00:21:40,920 --> 00:21:44,840
and now you're going to shift down to maybe a 
different tier of customers and you're trying  

264
00:21:44,840 --> 00:21:50,400
to set up some more of a self-serve kind of 
a sales motion. You need to understand that. 

265
00:21:50,400 --> 00:21:55,640
Another common time is when you're selling but 
something's not going quite as well as maybe you  

266
00:21:55,640 --> 00:21:59,880
hoped it was going. You've already launched 
and you want to just kind of troubleshoot,  

267
00:21:59,880 --> 00:22:07,080
like, "What's going on? We have some traction, 
maybe, but it's not what we wanted," or "We're  

268
00:22:07,080 --> 00:22:15,840
getting that very polite, encouraging feedback, 
which sounds good, but it's really no. Let's go  

269
00:22:15,840 --> 00:22:20,640
dive in and find out." So those are the big 
key things of the times of when to do it.

270
00:22:20,640 --> 00:22:26,160
Okay, let's actually get into the steps. I 
believe there's six core steps to the process.

271
00:22:26,160 --> 00:22:26,920
Okay. Yeah.

272
00:22:26,920 --> 00:22:29,840
Okay, cool. Where do you start? What's step one?

273
00:22:29,840 --> 00:22:35,400
Yeah. So step one is what I do is I plan about 
a 45-minute meeting with the team. Again,  

274
00:22:35,400 --> 00:22:38,800
it's really important to have that core team 
together and have this conversation about what  

275
00:22:38,800 --> 00:22:43,680
are the key questions, basically, "What do 
you wish you would know about your product,  

276
00:22:43,680 --> 00:22:48,680
about your customers? What's getting in the way?"
One of the most common ways that we ask this is,  

277
00:22:48,680 --> 00:22:51,760
basically, "What keeps you up at night?" 
because founders and product people  

278
00:22:51,760 --> 00:22:55,440
have... There's a bazillion things that 
they're kind of bubbling in their head,  

279
00:22:55,440 --> 00:23:00,200
that they're worrying about. But that often gets 
them to step back and be like, "Oh, what I'm  

280
00:23:00,200 --> 00:23:07,240
really unsure is this. What's going to happen? 
How will people respond to this fundamental  

281
00:23:07,240 --> 00:23:14,840
concept or this idea or how will they use it?"
I have a set of questions that I'll go through  

282
00:23:14,840 --> 00:23:20,240
with them to help prompt and elicit, "What are 
those big things that you wish you knew? What  

283
00:23:20,240 --> 00:23:27,200
would have to be true for this to succeed? What 
are your hypotheses and what are your assumptions  

284
00:23:27,200 --> 00:23:34,320
about the product, about the customer? Who do 
you think this is or not, and why? What are those  

285
00:23:34,320 --> 00:23:38,960
nagging debates on the team, those kinds of things 
that keep coming up over and over and you're like,  

286
00:23:38,960 --> 00:23:43,400
'Oh, for God's sakes, let's go get some 
information and answer the question'?" It's some  

287
00:23:43,400 --> 00:23:48,800
of these things. So we have that initial meeting 
to kind of detail, what do we need to answer?

288
00:23:48,800 --> 00:23:53,040
Awesome. And this informs other... I 
imagine, all the things you do next.  

289
00:23:53,040 --> 00:23:56,760
And so in the PDF [inaudible 00:23:55] 
too, in the show notes, you can see all  

290
00:23:56,760 --> 00:24:01,720
these questions and run through them yourself. 
Okay, cool. So that's step one. What's step two?

291
00:24:01,720 --> 00:24:07,680
So step two is, based on what you want to learn, 
now let's figure out who is the bullseye customer  

292
00:24:07,680 --> 00:24:13,680
that we need to talk to to answer that question.
It all starts with those key questions that you  

293
00:24:13,680 --> 00:24:19,280
have, because if the question is about, let's 
say, big questions about onboarding, well, if the  

294
00:24:19,280 --> 00:24:23,520
questions are about onboarding flow, then you're 
going to want to talk to new customers, somebody  

295
00:24:23,520 --> 00:24:28,040
who's fresh to this to see, how do they get 
through or how do they understand what this is?  

296
00:24:28,040 --> 00:24:31,440
Whereas if you're talking about something that's 
a new feature that's already in your product,  

297
00:24:31,440 --> 00:24:37,320
then you'd be talking to existing customers. So 
that's an example where if I understand what the  

298
00:24:37,320 --> 00:24:42,280
questions are, I can kind of work backwards 
to understand, who do I need to talk to? 

299
00:24:42,280 --> 00:24:48,400
And then based on that, what I do is run what 
I call a bullseye exercise. So it's, again,  

300
00:24:48,400 --> 00:24:52,960
essentially another kind of interview. Get 
the team together, and I pepper them with a  

301
00:24:52,960 --> 00:24:58,720
lot of questions to figure out exactly who is this 
bullseye customer that we've been talking about.  

302
00:24:58,720 --> 00:25:07,000
And the reason I love doing this as a team 
is that what happens invariably is having  

303
00:25:07,000 --> 00:25:12,920
that conversation before we've even gotten to 
any interviews is super clarifying for a team,  

304
00:25:12,920 --> 00:25:18,040
because they tend to get a shorthand 
about who their customers are. 

305
00:25:18,040 --> 00:25:21,400
And this is a way... And I just keep asking 
questions, like, "Well, what do you mean by  

306
00:25:21,400 --> 00:25:27,880
that? So when you say you're building a delivery 
service for people who get specialty medications  

307
00:25:27,880 --> 00:25:35,080
delivered, specialty prescription medications, 
who exactly is that? It's not everybody."  

308
00:25:35,080 --> 00:25:39,960
And so we start narrowing it down. So they 
start having those conversations, debates,  

309
00:25:39,960 --> 00:25:44,760
arguments about who it is, and just having that is 
really clarifying for the team. Like, "Oh, well,  

310
00:25:44,760 --> 00:25:48,840
I hadn't thought about that. Yeah, I guess it's 
true. Maybe it's not everybody who has that. It's  

311
00:25:48,840 --> 00:25:53,480
only people who have this kind of condition 
or this set of conditions or these needs."

312
00:25:53,480 --> 00:25:57,840
And to follow that thread real quick, I imagine 
people's natural inclination is not to narrow  

313
00:25:57,840 --> 00:26:02,640
it too much, because there's always like, "Why 
would we exclude this big market opportunity?  

314
00:26:02,640 --> 00:26:07,640
Why would it have to be so narrow?" Can you 
just speak a little bit to just why it's so  

315
00:26:07,640 --> 00:26:14,080
important to get very, very narrow? Andy 
Johns, on a newsletter post I wrote once,  

316
00:26:14,080 --> 00:26:18,240
he described it as, "It should feel 
comically narrow." Does that resonate?

317
00:26:18,240 --> 00:26:22,040
I love that. Yeah, I hadn't heard that phrase, 
but I love that. Yeah, comically narrow is  

318
00:26:22,040 --> 00:26:25,160
exactly what it is. And there are times that 
teams will just be like, "Oh, for God's sakes,  

319
00:26:25,160 --> 00:26:34,080
Margolis, this is too much." The reason that 
I do that is I'm pushing them to identify a  

320
00:26:34,080 --> 00:26:40,920
person who they all would agree, "This person, 
if we present this value prop that we think  

321
00:26:40,920 --> 00:26:45,920
we're going to build and this problem we think 
we're solving, we are all convinced... Or it's  

322
00:26:45,920 --> 00:26:50,680
our best guess." It's fine if you're not sure, 
but, "We are pretty convinced that that's the  

323
00:26:50,680 --> 00:26:59,400
person who will say, 'Yeah, I need this thing.'"
I'm kind of running an experiment, right? It's a  

324
00:26:59,400 --> 00:27:07,720
way to reduce variables for me and then to get 
that specific, and then I recruit a bunch of  

325
00:27:07,720 --> 00:27:14,720
the people who match that very particular set of 
characteristics. And they're people, so there's  

326
00:27:14,720 --> 00:27:21,960
still some variation, but it's a way for us to 
test that. If there's too much variation, then  

327
00:27:21,960 --> 00:27:26,600
what happens? At the end of the day, you're like, 
"That was kind of a mush. I'm not really sure what  

328
00:27:26,600 --> 00:27:34,400
we learned. Was it because it was just people had 
mixed feelings or was it because there was just  

329
00:27:34,400 --> 00:27:38,680
not enough consistency? We had too many variables 
in there. I don't know what we learned here."

330
00:27:38,680 --> 00:27:43,520
So I think what's nice about this is this initial 
list you're making of bullseye potential customers  

331
00:27:43,520 --> 00:27:48,120
and attributes is not exactly going to be 
who you go after. Once you figure this out,  

332
00:27:48,880 --> 00:27:54,440
you want to be very confident these group 
will absolutely love what you're presenting,  

333
00:27:54,440 --> 00:27:58,520
because you're trying to learn as much as 
you can from the people that most love it.  

334
00:27:58,520 --> 00:28:03,000
And then from that, you can get a little 
less narrow to actually pitch your product.

335
00:28:03,000 --> 00:28:09,280
Right. And most often what happens is we do this, 
we define it our best, right? It's our hypothesis.  

336
00:28:09,280 --> 00:28:13,480
It's our best guess. The team is always very 
expert. I'm not. I'm always showing up as the  

337
00:28:13,480 --> 00:28:18,720
noob in whatever this business is. The team is 
expert, and so this is very informed. It's not  

338
00:28:18,720 --> 00:28:25,480
like we're guessing. But we go through this, and 
by the time after we've done these interviews,  

339
00:28:25,480 --> 00:28:30,080
the goal is to figure out, "Was this right or 
not? Or in what ways do we need to adjust?"  

340
00:28:30,080 --> 00:28:35,160
That's a big piece of the outcome, is adjusting 
that definition of your bullseye customer. 

341
00:28:35,160 --> 00:28:40,640
And often what happens is through the course 
of that Bullseye Customer Sprint, you learn,  

342
00:28:40,640 --> 00:28:45,920
"Oh, it turns out there's actually this other 
distinguishing characteristic we didn't realize,  

343
00:28:45,920 --> 00:28:50,600
or maybe it validates what we knew." But 
often, "We didn't quite realize that. This  

344
00:28:50,600 --> 00:28:58,400
other thing is popping up where we're seeing 
heat from people. Oh, wow, that's interesting.  

345
00:28:58,400 --> 00:29:02,080
Let's dive in a little more." I mean, I 
can walk through an example if you want.

346
00:29:02,080 --> 00:29:03,339
Yeah, that'd be awesome. Then-

347
00:29:03,339 --> 00:29:03,360
[inaudible 00:29:03].

348
00:29:03,360 --> 00:29:06,480
Yeah, yeah. And I think even just like, 
what are some examples of attributes?  

349
00:29:06,480 --> 00:29:09,040
What's the list of attributes 
you should be thinking about?

350
00:29:09,040 --> 00:29:11,520
Let me just give you an example. I think a 
lot of this stuff we're talking about, it  

351
00:29:11,520 --> 00:29:17,240
starts to get a little abstract. So I was 
working with a company that was developing  

352
00:29:18,280 --> 00:29:23,360
a new delivery service for people 
who have specialty prescriptions,  

353
00:29:23,360 --> 00:29:27,640
medications. So these are the kinds of 
medications that are expensive and for very  

354
00:29:28,280 --> 00:29:31,440
specialized chronic diseases. This is not 
the kind of thing you're getting at Rite  

355
00:29:31,440 --> 00:29:37,440
Aid. And there's something very special about this 
company, and then I can mention that afterwards. 

356
00:29:37,440 --> 00:29:41,920
But the fundamental thing for them to figure out 
was, before they can build out the logistics of  

357
00:29:41,920 --> 00:29:47,960
this, they're trying to figure out, "Do we need 
to target something that is for delivery like  

358
00:29:47,960 --> 00:29:52,480
ASAP?" These are really important medications 
for very serious diseases. Is it like, "Oh,  

359
00:29:52,480 --> 00:29:57,240
my gosh, I need the next pill. Get it to me 
as fast as you can"? Or is it like, "Well,  

360
00:29:57,240 --> 00:30:02,000
I can wait till a day or two, but I need it 
between 2:00 and 2:15 PM," like if I knew that?  

361
00:30:02,000 --> 00:30:07,800
And then who exactly is this bullseye customer? 
We want to know, what's really the fundamental  

362
00:30:07,800 --> 00:30:11,960
issue or problem that we're solving here? 
And so they wanted to answer those questions. 

363
00:30:11,960 --> 00:30:17,600
And so we go through this process, and so those 
are the key questions. And then the customers  

364
00:30:17,600 --> 00:30:22,360
that they're after, I know, okay, well, it's not 
going to be everybody with specialty medications.  

365
00:30:22,360 --> 00:30:26,960
And so as we start teasing through that and 
thinking about it, I want to think about,  

366
00:30:26,960 --> 00:30:31,320
