01:01:15,520 --> 01:01:19,600
Right, so you have people coming. You're 
scheduled, so people are showing up on  

740
01:01:19,600 --> 01:01:22,880
Thursday. We're going to start doing interviews, 
so you have to draft your interview guide. 

741
01:01:22,880 --> 01:01:28,840
What these interviews are going to look like, 
in the course of that watch party, it's five  

742
01:01:28,840 --> 01:01:35,000
one-hour interviews. Each interview is a two-part 
interview. So the first part of the interview  

743
01:01:35,000 --> 01:01:40,560
is this discovery interview where I'm asking 
people about their existing and past experiences  

744
01:01:40,560 --> 01:01:45,960
and attitudes and opinions about whatever this 
part of their life is. "How did you previously  

745
01:01:45,960 --> 01:01:50,840
get your medications delivered? What worked? What 
didn't work? Tell me about a time when it totally  

746
01:01:50,840 --> 01:01:55,360
went sideways. Tell me about a time it worked 
perfectly." So we go through that and have that. 

747
01:01:55,360 --> 01:02:02,880
About halfway through that interview, I shift to 
comparing and contrasting these prototypes. So the  

748
01:02:02,880 --> 01:02:09,120
comparing and contrasting is I'm presenting each 
prototype and people are responding to that and  

749
01:02:09,120 --> 01:02:14,800
telling me what they see, what this is, and then 
the responding to what each of these prototypes  

750
01:02:14,800 --> 01:02:18,440
is, what they like, what they don't like, what's 
important, what's not important. Some parts that  

751
01:02:18,440 --> 01:02:22,680
they don't comment on is fine. If that just 
doesn't even register, that's good to know. And  

752
01:02:22,680 --> 01:02:28,600
then I'm having them compare and contrast.
So by having three different prototypes,  

753
01:02:28,600 --> 01:02:33,720
it's enough for them to then sort of step back 
and not pick a winner, but be able to say, "Oh,  

754
01:02:33,720 --> 01:02:37,960
I like this aspect of this one. I like the fact 
that this one's being delivered by a pharmacist,  

755
01:02:37,960 --> 01:02:42,920
but I really prefer that this other one is a 
15-minute window," for example. And so they're  

756
01:02:42,920 --> 01:02:47,960
kind of teasing out, what are the best pieces of 
each of these? And that's really what I'm looking  

757
01:02:47,960 --> 01:02:53,080
for through the course of this conversation, 
is I want to grab the best bits and pieces,  

758
01:02:53,080 --> 01:02:58,400
the best Lego pieces, so I can then go construct 
the ideal version next, because none of these...  

759
01:02:58,400 --> 01:03:03,360
Again, I'm not going to build probably any 
one of those. I'm looking for the best pieces. 

760
01:03:03,360 --> 01:03:06,720
And through the arc of that conversation, 
by doing the first half where I've had the  

761
01:03:06,720 --> 01:03:11,400
discovery conversation, it gives me a huge amount 
of context to understand their feedback about  

762
01:03:11,400 --> 01:03:17,520
the prototypes, because there will be times 
when they'll say things or tell us something,  

763
01:03:17,520 --> 01:03:21,040
and because we heard the first part... 
They'll tell us something about the prototype,  

764
01:03:21,040 --> 01:03:25,160
and because of what we heard in the first part, 
we'll understand why. Like, "Oh, it's because  

765
01:03:25,160 --> 01:03:28,840
they had that other experience in the past where 
that thing went totally haywire, when something  

766
01:03:28,840 --> 01:03:34,400
like that happened, and they don't have trust 
in that. Now I know why that's the situation." 

767
01:03:34,400 --> 01:03:39,240
And it's very, very, very common that when 
teams are watching this, they're always like,  

768
01:03:39,240 --> 01:03:45,240
"For Christ's sake, Margolis, would you just get 
to the prototypes? Why are you just talking to  

769
01:03:45,240 --> 01:03:49,120
them about all this other stuff? And you're 
just chit-chatting with them. Ugh. Show them  

770
01:03:49,120 --> 01:03:54,040
prototypes." And so we always have to remind 
people, "No, no, this is really important."  

771
01:03:54,040 --> 01:03:57,480
Partly, you're also just learning a lot. You 
hear those stories, which is what you want  

772
01:03:57,480 --> 01:04:04,320
to get, but it provides a lot of context for 
understanding their reaction to the prototypes.

773
01:04:04,320 --> 01:04:07,800
I love all that context that you shared. This 
is the step I think where everyone gets kind  

774
01:04:07,800 --> 01:04:13,120
of scared or afraid or thinking they're doing 
this wrong, they're biasing people. So in the  

775
01:04:13,120 --> 01:04:16,920
book that we'll link to, you give them a guide 
for how to write out this whole interview guide.  

776
01:04:16,920 --> 01:04:22,040
I have the book here, and I'm just looking at 
an example where it's like there's the warmup,  

777
01:04:22,040 --> 01:04:25,720
there's the introduction, and then it's like 
your current experience with this problem,  

778
01:04:26,240 --> 01:04:30,040
cost, depends on the problem space.
But I love in the warmup, big smile. "Hi,  

779
01:04:30,040 --> 01:04:35,800
thanks for helping me with this. Thanks 
for signing the NDA. I'm dialing in from  

780
01:04:35,800 --> 01:04:38,600
Seattle. Where have I reached you?" And 
then it's like, "How's the weather where  

781
01:04:38,600 --> 01:04:42,640
you are?" So it's all these nice little 
questions you can ask to keep it light,  

782
01:04:42,640 --> 01:04:47,160
and then just a few examples of questions 
you ask in this example where it's about  

783
01:04:47,160 --> 01:04:50,960
the medication. It's like, "Do you currently 
have prescription medication that you have  

784
01:04:50,960 --> 01:04:55,720
to order and refill? How many? If I may 
ask, what are they? When was the last  

785
01:04:55,720 --> 01:05:00,040
time you filled a prescription?" and on and on.
So it's kind of this whole set of questions just  

786
01:05:00,040 --> 01:05:07,160
to help understand their worldview around 
this problem and the context around it.

787
01:05:07,160 --> 01:05:11,680
And the way that I think about it is that I'm 
building an arc in that conversation. And so it  

788
01:05:11,680 --> 01:05:16,640
starts, like you said, it's just chit-chat about 
the weather and where you are and whatever. Do I  

789
01:05:16,640 --> 01:05:21,040
care what the weather... I don't care what 
the weather is like, but what I'm trying  

790
01:05:21,040 --> 01:05:28,200
to do is build some rapport fast with somebody.
Again, it gets back to this idea of humble inquiry  

791
01:05:28,200 --> 01:05:33,320
where I'm trying to build a connection with the 
person. I'm trying to make them feel comfortable,  

792
01:05:33,320 --> 01:05:37,920
because they usually are showing 
up, they want to make you happy,  

793
01:05:37,920 --> 01:05:42,560
but they don't really understand... It's awkward. 
It's super weird. Like, "I'm going to talk to this  

794
01:05:42,560 --> 01:05:47,880
weird dude. He's paying me to tell him what turns 
out to be a bunch of personal stuff, and we're  

795
01:05:47,880 --> 01:05:54,520
never going to talk again. But am I doing a good 
job?" It's odd. And so I'm trying to put them at  

796
01:05:54,520 --> 01:05:59,880
ease and I'm trying to encourage them and make 
it clear they're the expert in this situation,  

797
01:05:59,880 --> 01:06:05,560
but they don't really know what's going to happen.
And so I'm building this arc slowly, hopefully  

798
01:06:05,560 --> 01:06:10,000
not too slowly, to get them talking. So one of 
the most important things is when you're doing  

799
01:06:10,000 --> 01:06:15,360
that interview, smile. You have to start with 
the big smile. Even if you're on the phone,  

800
01:06:15,360 --> 01:06:19,800
it totally changes the way your voice sounds. 
And what I'm often looking for in those first  

801
01:06:19,800 --> 01:06:23,840
few minutes is, are they smiling back? Can I get 
the person to smile back at me? And then I'm like,  

802
01:06:23,840 --> 01:06:28,000
"Okay, we're good. I'm getting them 
responsive and getting them talking."

803
01:06:28,000 --> 01:06:32,920
I love that tip. And again, I think a lot 
of people that aren't researches are just  

804
01:06:32,920 --> 01:06:39,040
going to, "Oh, I don't know. This feels weird." 
Something that should be reassuring is mostly,  

805
01:06:39,040 --> 01:06:44,320
you're just asking questions. It's 
on them. You're just asking questions  

806
01:06:44,320 --> 01:06:49,480
and your job is not to say anything, 
almost, just keep asking questions.

807
01:06:49,480 --> 01:06:55,040
Yeah, and to be really genuinely curious. I 
think that's really... Again, it's to this  

808
01:06:55,040 --> 01:07:01,040
mindset, this difference between selling... I 
have to genuinely want to understand and see  

809
01:07:01,040 --> 01:07:06,840
the world and my product through their eyes. 
And you're going to hear stuff that is wrong,  

810
01:07:06,840 --> 01:07:10,400
you know doesn't make sense, or you're like, 
"That's weird. What is that?" And you just  

811
01:07:10,400 --> 01:07:17,840
have to, not dismiss that, but dig in and try 
to understand, like, "Why do you think that?  

812
01:07:18,720 --> 01:07:24,080
What gives you that impression?" That's what 
you're trying to learn, right? And just smile,  

813
01:07:24,080 --> 01:07:29,960
genuine curiosity, and focus on that person 
in front of you will get you pretty far.

814
01:07:29,960 --> 01:07:32,840
Any other tips on this step 
for folks that are like, "Okay,  

815
01:07:32,840 --> 01:07:37,600
I'm going to try this myself. I'm going to 
start interviewing folks"? Any other tips,  

816
01:07:37,600 --> 01:07:40,680
anything else important you 
think is worth mentioning?

817
01:07:40,680 --> 01:07:45,280
Yeah. Practice, it makes a difference. 
It's a hard skill. It seems like, oh,  

818
01:07:45,280 --> 01:07:52,400
everybody talks to everybody, but it's different.
When I do these, and I've interviewed thousands of  

819
01:07:52,400 --> 01:08:01,680
people at this point, I have a different character 
mode that I put my head in. And so I literally,  

820
01:08:01,680 --> 01:08:06,040
before I start an interview, I stop, I take a 
deep breath, and I kind of put on that smile  

821
01:08:06,040 --> 01:08:14,200
and I put on my listener character where I am 
embodying these things, this extreme curiosity,  

822
01:08:14,200 --> 01:08:20,160
this focus on the person, this engagement, 
which is quite different from my normal,  

823
01:08:20,800 --> 01:08:28,600
more cynical, skeptical personality, to the 
point where if my kids have overheard, like,  

824
01:08:28,600 --> 01:08:31,920
"Who is that dude? Because that does 
not sound like Dad, whoever is talking  

825
01:08:31,920 --> 01:08:37,200
to that person." But it's a different mode 
in my head where I'm in interviewer mode. 

826
01:08:40,200 --> 01:08:43,880
Maybe that's just me, but you might 
develop kind of that other character,  

827
01:08:43,880 --> 01:08:48,120
especially if you're a founder used to 
pitching, you can have your listener character.

828
01:08:48,120 --> 01:08:52,200
Okay. That was an awesome tip. Okay, and so 
I think then the next step is the final step,  

829
01:08:52,200 --> 01:08:54,680
which is the watch party 
where you actually do this.

830
01:08:54,680 --> 01:09:01,000
Yeah. This is awesome. So this is like 
our magic hack for banging all this stuff  

831
01:09:01,000 --> 01:09:06,400
together. Everything is coming together in 
this watch party. So in this watch party,  

832
01:09:06,400 --> 01:09:09,840
we have... Again, I'm conducting 
the interview. I'm off on Zoom,  

833
01:09:09,840 --> 01:09:15,200
one-on-one conducting these interviews. In 
the watch party, Vanessa Cho, Kate Aronowitz,  

834
01:09:15,200 --> 01:09:20,120
my amazing design partners, often are facilitating 
the group there. And so what they're having the  

835
01:09:20,120 --> 01:09:27,160
team do is take notes and go through these 
debrief sessions in between each interview. 

836
01:09:27,160 --> 01:09:31,160
And so we have a very particular way that we 
structure all of that, and it's very important  

837
01:09:31,160 --> 01:09:36,720
that the team is all in there and watching and 
doing this together. So I'm in Zoom, I have it set  

838
01:09:36,720 --> 01:09:41,800
up so it's livestreaming to them. So they're not 
in my Zoom. It's not like 20 of us with a bunch of  

839
01:09:41,800 --> 01:09:46,480
heads watching the person. It's really important 
to me that it's just me and the customer that I'm  

840
01:09:46,480 --> 01:09:53,840
talking to directly. So they're all livestreaming 
it. They're taking notes, so they're in a Google  

841
01:09:53,840 --> 01:09:57,400
Doc, or Notion or Doc or whatever 
you want, collaboratively doing that. 

842
01:09:57,400 --> 01:10:02,200
And so people are assigned roles, so take turns 
taking notes, because it's pretty intense. We  

843
01:10:02,200 --> 01:10:08,640
have people manually taking notes and not using 
AI to take notes. The reason for this is, what  

844
01:10:08,640 --> 01:10:14,160
we've found is we want people to lean in to this 
experience. We want you to focus and engage and  

845
01:10:14,160 --> 01:10:20,360
pay a lot of attention, and if you know somebody 
else is taking notes, it tends to maybe make you  

846
01:10:20,360 --> 01:10:24,240
lean out a little bit, or maybe you check your 
Slack or you're looking at email or something.  

847
01:10:24,240 --> 01:10:32,000
And so it's about keeping you really engaged 
and working. So it's a working watch party. 

848
01:10:32,000 --> 01:10:36,960
So we take turns, we've assigned roles so people 
know, "Okay, interview two, Lenny and Margolis  

849
01:10:36,960 --> 01:10:41,440
are going to be taking notes. That's fine." And 
then there's also a Slack channel, usually, in the  

850
01:10:41,440 --> 01:10:43,600
background, because there's a lot of other 
chatter, like, "Wait, what did they say? They're  

851
01:10:43,600 --> 01:10:46,320
talking about this. They mentioned that product. 
Has anybody heard of that?" So that's really  

852
01:10:46,320 --> 01:10:52,360
important kind of going in the background. Vanessa 
or Kate also monitors that, so that's the way that  

853
01:10:52,360 --> 01:10:59,400
somebody can pass me notes to ask specific other 
questions. I can't do the interview and track  

854
01:10:59,400 --> 01:11:04,920
the notes and Slack. My brain can't handle that.
So they're in there, and then I have a chat window  

855
01:11:04,920 --> 01:11:10,640
open just with Kate or Vanessa, and so they'll pop 
me questions as they come up. We usually ask teams  

856
01:11:10,640 --> 01:11:16,760
to be pretty judicious about that, because if I 
get a question like that, it could go a certain  

857
01:11:16,760 --> 01:11:20,880
way, as you know, right? You ask a question, 
you don't know where it's going to go. And so if  

858
01:11:20,880 --> 01:11:25,240
it's really important or you see something where 
clearly I've misunderstood something, clarify it. 

859
01:11:26,720 --> 01:11:33,400
So they're taking notes. This debrief is in a 
spreadsheet that I've set up so that there are key  

860
01:11:33,400 --> 01:11:39,480
things that we wanted to learn, and so those are 
specified in that spreadsheet for each study that  

861
01:11:39,480 --> 01:11:45,840
I'm doing. I'm like, "These were the key things." 
Those are not the questions that I'm asking in  

862
01:11:45,840 --> 01:11:49,720
the interview, but they're the things, again, 
these key questions that we wanted to learn,  

863
01:11:49,720 --> 01:11:53,640
which is different from what I'm asking. And 
so we're just capturing in that half hour, the  

864
01:11:53,640 --> 01:12:00,360
decider, whoever owns the product or the founder 
is leading that because they're the decider. And  

865
01:12:00,360 --> 01:12:03,280
they're leading, getting input from everybody 
and filling in and answering those questions. 

866
01:12:03,280 --> 01:12:08,160
So then you can imagine you have... That 
first column is that set of questions,  

867
01:12:09,280 --> 01:12:12,720
so those are the rows of the questions, and 
then each participant is another column. So  

868
01:12:12,720 --> 01:12:16,280
we're doing participant one, we're capturing 
it after the second one. So we end up with  

869
01:12:16,280 --> 01:12:21,560
the detailed notes. We have the recording of my 
interview. Those are the thickest, deepest levels  

870
01:12:21,560 --> 01:12:27,520
of this. Then we're distilling it down into this 
debrief sheet for each one, and so then you have  

871
01:12:27,520 --> 01:12:32,800
a spreadsheet that's like the high level steps. 
You can look across it at the end of the day. 

872
01:12:32,800 --> 01:12:35,680
At the very last thing, at the end 
of the day, after the final debrief,  

873
01:12:35,680 --> 01:12:41,160
we do a big takeaways form. So I create a 
Google Form, and it just is basically like,  

874
01:12:41,160 --> 01:12:45,840
"How many interviews did you watch?" just to 
check, and then, "What's your first big takeaway,  

875
01:12:45,840 --> 01:12:51,520
second, third? How would you adjust your 
definition of the bullseye customer here?  

876
01:12:52,080 --> 01:12:56,240
What do you think are the next steps or what are 
your big questions, open questions and concerns?" 

877
01:12:56,240 --> 01:13:01,640
And so each person then takes 5, 10 minutes 
independently, separately, individually,  

878
01:13:01,640 --> 01:13:08,040
quietly, and just everybody mutes their video 
and fills that out. And it's a way to grab a  

879
01:13:08,040 --> 01:13:12,840
snapshot from the whole team of like, "What did 
we really learn? This was the important things  

880
01:13:12,840 --> 01:13:18,040
that we had set out to do. What did we learn?" 
And it captures that. So then again, that fills  

881
01:13:18,040 --> 01:13:24,320
out a big spreadsheet and we then review that. The 
decider kind of goes through it and talks about,  

882
01:13:24,320 --> 01:13:26,960
"What are the key patterns? What are the 
things that we've learned here as a team?" 

883
01:13:26,960 --> 01:13:32,200
And there's this remarkable amount, usually, of 
consensus, of alignment about, "What is this?  

884
01:13:32,200 --> 01:13:37,960
What do we need to do next?" What I love seeing is 
that, quite frankly, one of the most common things  

885
01:13:37,960 --> 01:13:44,480
across all of these businesses, all these sites, 
all these studies, is that one of the things that  

886
01:13:44,480 --> 01:13:52,440
people say we need to do next is more research. 
Even though these are all teams who've said,  

887
01:13:52,440 --> 01:13:57,040
"We talk to our customers all the time," we 
go through this and they're always like, "Oh,  

888
01:13:57,040 --> 01:14:04,520
yeah, this looks really different than what 
we were doing. We didn't know this stuff." 

889
01:14:04,520 --> 01:14:10,040
One of the other things I want to mention 
is we do this thing before the watch party  

890
01:14:10,040 --> 01:14:13,640
where we get everybody predict what 
they think they're going to learn.

891
01:14:13,640 --> 01:14:15,320
Oh, I love that.

892
01:14:15,320 --> 01:14:20,320
And this is really valuable for a bunch 
of different reasons. So it's a way to  

893
01:14:20,320 --> 01:14:25,280
capture a snapshot before we do the 
interviews of, what do you actually  

894
01:14:25,280 --> 01:14:29,400
think is going to happen? And we have to 
push people to be specific. It's not, "Oh,  

895
01:14:29,400 --> 01:14:33,400
we'll find out what they think of our concept." 
Yeah, yeah, I know we're going to learn that,  

896
01:14:33,400 --> 01:14:40,600
but what do you actually think is going to be 
the outcome? People will prefer ASAP delivery  

897
01:14:40,600 --> 01:14:47,120
of their medications, and whatever. What is 
your hypothesis of what's going to happen here? 

898
01:14:47,120 --> 01:14:51,040
And that helps me do a couple things. One 
is it helps me make sure that I'm tailoring  

899
01:14:51,040 --> 01:14:53,880
the interview guide and everything the 
right way, because it's another check,  

900
01:14:53,880 --> 01:14:58,520
like am I understanding what you want to 
get out of this? It's a snapshot of what  

901
01:14:58,520 --> 01:15:02,480
we wanted to learn. And then what happens is 
after we go through the big takeaways at the  

902
01:15:02,480 --> 01:15:09,200
end of the whole study, it's very valuable to go 
back and say, "How does what we learned compare  

903
01:15:09,200 --> 01:15:14,280
to what you thought?" because there's this... 
Any researchers out there listening to this  

904
01:15:14,280 --> 01:15:18,480
will be familiar with this idea. There's this 
hindsight bias that happens, which is as you've  

905
01:15:18,480 --> 01:15:24,960
gone through the process, it's very difficult 
to remember that you didn't already know this. 

906
01:15:25,560 --> 01:15:29,520
And so after you've gone through a research 
study, very often, people are like, "Well,  

907
01:15:30,080 --> 01:15:33,120
that seems obvious. We kind of knew that 
that was going to happen." You're like,  

908
01:15:33,120 --> 01:15:39,760
"No, no. Let's look back at a day ago, what we 
all thought. And we actually have learned a lot,  

909
01:15:39,760 --> 01:15:44,000
which is awesome. That's the goal. We've learned 
it an enormous amount." And it's not to catch  

910
01:15:44,000 --> 01:15:50,000
anybody out, but it's really valuable to 
have this snapshot and to, quite frankly,  

911
01:15:50,000 --> 01:15:55,400
just help show the value of the research, like, 
"We learned things. Or maybe we didn't. Maybe you  

912
01:15:55,400 --> 01:16:00,400
were all right, which is awesome. And now we 
know, and we can move forward twice as fast."

913
01:16:00,400 --> 01:16:05,840
The point you made about how most people after 
this are like, "Wow, this is not what I expected  

914
01:16:05,840 --> 01:16:10,360
and I want to do this more," I know that feeling 
so well. Every time you're like, "No, I don't need  

915
01:16:10,360 --> 01:16:15,000
to talk to customers. I understand what we need to 
build," and then you do, you're like, "Holy shit,  

916
01:16:15,000 --> 01:16:20,080
why aren't we doing this all the time? What 
are we doing?" That's such a powerful feeling.

917
01:16:20,080 --> 01:16:24,360
Yeah. There's this other thing that I think is 
worth mentioning that I've come across, which,  

918
01:16:24,360 --> 01:16:29,960
when we do this set of predictions, so again, 
it's across all different kinds of businesses,  

919
01:16:29,960 --> 01:16:34,360
all different kinds of domains, there's 
certain patterns that I've noticed that  

920
01:16:34,360 --> 01:16:41,640
show up over and over about mispredictions. 
There's a pattern of the kinds of things  

921
01:16:41,640 --> 01:16:48,840
that show up over and over that I think of 
as these common blind spots, and I think  

922
01:16:48,840 --> 01:16:55,320
it's attributed... I can attribute it to this, 
there's this concept of the curse of knowledge. 

923
01:16:55,320 --> 01:17:01,600
So I'm working with lots of teams who are 
deep experts in their space. I'm not. I'm  

924
01:17:01,600 --> 01:17:05,280
always showing up as the noob, like, "Okay, 
what is your business? What are we doing?"  

925
01:17:05,280 --> 01:17:08,440
But they have deep expertise. And 
when somebody has deep expertise,  

926
01:17:08,440 --> 01:17:16,840
it's very difficult to imagine that other people 
don't know what you know. It's very hard to put  

927
01:17:16,840 --> 01:17:25,040
yourself in their shoes, right? And you just 
think, "Well, doesn't everybody know this?" 

928
01:17:25,040 --> 01:17:29,680
And so what that leads to is these 
key blind spots that are very common,  

929
01:17:29,680 --> 01:17:35,560
which is there's an overestimation of how 
much your customer knows about the thing,  

930
01:17:35,560 --> 01:17:42,040
maybe how big a problem they even perceive it 
to be, how much they're willing to pay for it,  

931
01:17:42,040 --> 01:17:49,120
which is connected, and where they are on their 
journey to be ready to buy this thing. Like, "Oh,  

932
01:17:49,120 --> 01:17:57,280
wait, they're not ready yet? Wait." Right? They're 
not there yet, or we haven't figured out who the  

933
01:17:57,280 --> 01:18:02,000
right people are who are the bullseye, but people 
overestimate those kinds of things. And it's  

934
01:18:02,000 --> 01:18:07,640
really common blind spots that we find over and 
over across a lot of businesses with expert teams.

935
01:18:07,640 --> 01:18:14,360
That makes sense. Most startups realize what 
they're trying to build, nobody really cares  

936
01:18:14,360 --> 01:18:19,480
about. So I get why that happens often.
